    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="1170"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1170">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> Papers</note>
                <head>No. 1170<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Joint Chiefs of Staff</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi> [<hi rend="italic"
                            >Babelsberg</hi>]</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1945-07-20">20 July 1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the President</hi>
                </p>
                <p>In the past we have experienced considerable delay in travel of individuals and
                    important official mail between the United States and Moscow. This situation is
                    now susceptible to considerable improvement if the air connection point were
                    shifted from Tehran to Berlin.</p>
                <p>Experience has shown that the Russians are extremely hesitant in coming to any
                    agreements with foreign countries regarding air travel for fear of establishing
                        prec<persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName>ts that might carry over into
                    the postwar period. Efforts to obtain Soviet agreement to a Berlin connecting
                    point have been made without success by both our military and diplomatic
                    representatives.</p>
                <p>There is a good likelihood that Marshal <persName corresp="#p_SGIV1"
                        >Stalin</persName> would accede to a personal request made by you, and it is
                    recommended that you either send the attached letter<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d1170fn1">
                        <ref target="#d1171">Document No. 1171</ref>. This paper bears the following
                        manuscript notation by <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1">Leahy</persName>:
                        “Letter delivered to <persName corresp="#p_SGIV1">Stalin</persName> 20 July
                            <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1">W. D. L.</persName>”</note> to Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGIV1">Stalin</persName> or discuss the matter with
                    him along the lines indicated.</p>
                <closer>For the Joint Chiefs of Staff:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">William</hi> D <hi rend="smallcaps">Leahy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Fleet Admiral, U. S. Navy, Chief of Staff to the Commander in
                        Chief of the Army and Navy.</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
